Experiment No.—9: IoT Protocol – Send Sensor Data Online 

a) Use HTTP or MQTT to push sensor values to a cloud server (e.g., Thingspeak) 
b) Implement publishing logic with timestamps 
c) Use Arduino/NodeMCU or Raspberry Pi as the publisher

Theoretical Steps, Code & Expected Output: 

(a) Use HTTP or MQTT to Push Sensor Values to a Cloud Server (ThingSpeak) – 
Theoretical 

Steps 
1. Create an account on the ThingSpeak IoT Cloud Platform. 
2. Create a new channel to store sensor data. 
3. Configure fields for sensor values (e.g., Temperature, Humidity). 
4. Note the Write API Key generated for the channel. 
5. Connect the IoT device (Raspberry Pi / NodeMCU / Arduino) to the internet. 
6. Write a program that sends sensor values to ThingSpeak using HTTP requests or 
MQTT publishing. 

Example HTTP Request Format 
https://api.thingspeak.com/update?api_key=YOUR_API_KEY&field1=value 
This request sends sensor data to the ThingSpeak server. 

Python Code Example (Raspberry Pi – HTTP Method) 

import requests 
import time 
 
api_key = "YOUR_API_KEY" 
url = "https://api.thingspeak.com/update" 
 
while True: 
    temperature = 26   # Example sensor value 
 
    payload = {'api_key': api_key, 'field1': temperature} 
    response = requests.get(url, params=payload) 
 
    print("Data Sent:", temperature) 
 
    time.sleep(15)

Expected Output 

Terminal Output: 

Data Sent: 26 
Data Sent: 27 
Data Sent: 28 

ThingSpeak dashboard displays sensor data graphically. 

Example channel graph: 

Time Temperature 
10:01 26 °C 
10:02 27 °C 
10:03 28 °C

(b) Implement Publishing Logic with Timestamps – Theoretical 

Steps 
1. Collect sensor data periodically from the device. 
2. Send the data to the cloud server at regular intervals. 
3. Each uploaded data entry is stored along with a timestamp. 
4. The timestamp indicates when the data was published.

CODE EXAMPLE

import requests 
import time 
from datetime import datetime 
 
api_key = "YOUR_API_KEY" 
url = "https://api.thingspeak.com/update" 
 
while True: 
    temperature = 27 
    timestamp = datetime.now() 
 
    payload = {'api_key': api_key, 'field1': temperature} 
    requests.get(url, params=payload) 
 
    print("Temperature:", temperature, "Time:", timestamp) 
 
    time.sleep(15)


Expected Output 

Terminal output example: 

Temperature: 27 Time: 2024-04-10 10:01:10 
Temperature: 28 Time: 2024-04-10 10:01:25 
Temperature: 27 Time: 2024-04-10 10:01:40 

ThingSpeak automatically logs data with timestamps. 

Example dataset: 

